A '''depocenter''' or '''depocentre''' in geology is the part of a [[sedimentary basin]] where a particular rock unit has its maximum thickness.<ref name="Schlumberger">{{Cite web |url=http://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/en/Terms/d/depocenter.aspx |title=depocenter |last=Schlumberger |series=Oilfield Glossary}}</ref> Depending on the controls on subsidence and the [[sedimentary environment]] the location of basin depocenters may vary with time, such as in active [[rift]] basins as [[extensional fault]]s grow, link or become abandoned.<ref name="Cowie_etal_2000">{{Cite journal |last=Cowie P.A. |last2=Gupta S. |last3=Dawers N.H. |year=2000 |title=Implications of fault array evolution for synrift depocentre development: insights from a numerical fault growth model |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/N_Dawers/publication/227644287_Implications_of_fault_array_evolution_for_synrift_depocentre_development_Insights_from_a_numerical_fault_growth_model/links/5a11d883a6fdccc2d79b6569/Implications-of-fault-array-evolution-for-synrift-depocentre-development-Insights-from-a-numerical-fault-growth-model.pdf |journal=Basin Research |volume=12 |issue=3–4 |pages=241–261 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2117.2000.00126.x}}</ref>

